# This ontology provides:
# 1. BFO-compliant modeling of domains as ICE with worldview weight profiles
# 2. Eight major life domains with comprehensive worldview weightings (0.0-1.0 scale)
# 3. Rationale and empirical evidence for each worldview weight in each domain
# 4. Integration with value-conflict-resolution.ttl (Step 4 contextualization)
# 5. Domain boundary dispute recognition and resolution strategies
# 6. 40+ philosophical and empirical sources
# 7. Critical notes explaining weight rationale and preventing misinterpretation

# Key domains modeled:
# - Healthcare: Materialism/Realism high (0.9), Spiritualism moderate (0.45)
# - Spiritual Formation: Spiritualism/Idealism/Pneumatism high (0.9+), Materialism low (0.3)
# - Education: Idealism/Rationalism/Dynamism high (0.85+), balanced objective/subjective
# - Vocational Choice: Monadism very high (0.95), authenticity paramount
# - Environmental Policy: Pneumatism/Materialism/Rationalism high (0.8+), unique integration
# - Relationship Ethics: Monadism/Psychism very high (0.9+), rationalism low (0.35)
# - Business/Economics: Materialism/Rationalism/Realism high (0.8+), instrumental focus
# - Scientific Research: Realism/Materialism very high (0.9+), spiritual minimal (0.15-0.2)

# Applications:
# - Step 4 of value conflict resolution: Apply domain weights to contextualize judgments
# - Prevent absurd applications: Spiritualism doesn't dominate surgery; materialism doesn't dominate prayer
# - Make context-sensitivity transparent: Explicit weights prevent hidden biases
# - Enable appropriate weighting without elimination: Low weight â‰  false or worthless

# Critical principles:
# - Domain weights reflect PURPOSE-APPROPRIATENESS, not universal truth claims
# - Low weight in one domain doesn't negate high weight in another domain
# - Weights are guidelines requiring judgment in application, not mechanical rules
# - Domain boundary disputes are common and require contextual wisdom
# - Multi-domain situations require integration of multiple weight profiles

